'''Rāhula''' ([[Pāli]] and Sanskrit) was the only son of [[Gautama Buddha|Siddhārtha Gautama (commonly known as the Buddha)]]  ({{nowrap|{{circa}} 563 or 480 {{en dash}}}} {{nowrap|483 or 400 BCE}}), and his wife and princess [[Yasodharā|Yaśodharā]]. He is mentioned in numerous Buddhist texts, from the [[Early Buddhist Texts|early period]] onward. Accounts about Rāhula indicate a mutual impact between Prince Siddhārtha's life and those of his family members. According to the [[Pali Canon|Pāli tradition]], Rāhula is born on the day of Prince Siddhārta's [[great renunciation|renunciation]], and is therefore named ''Rāhula'', meaning a fetter on the path to [[enlightenment (Buddhism)|enlightenment]]. According to the [[Mūlasarvāstivāda]] tradition, and numerous other [[post-canonical Buddhist texts|later sources]], however, Rāhula is only ''conceived'' on the day of Prince Siddhārtha, and is born six years later, when Prince Siddhārtha becomes enlightened as the [[Buddha (title)|Buddha]]. This long gestation period is explained by bad [[karma (Buddhism)|karma]] from previous lives of both Yaśodharā and of Rāhula himself, although more [[religious naturalism|naturalistic]] reasons are also given. As a result of the late birth, Yaśodharā needs to prove that Rāhula is really Prince Siddhārtha's son, which she eventually does successfully by an [[sacca-kiriya|act of truth]]. Historian {{ill|Wolfgang Schumann|de|Wolfgang Schumann (Historiker)}} has argued that Prince Siddhārtha conceived Rāhula and waited for his birth, to be able to leave the palace with the king and queen's permission, but Orientalist {{ill|Noël Péri|fr}} considered it more likely that Rāhula was born after Prince Siddhārtha left his palace.

Between seven and fifteen years after Rāhula is born, the Buddha returns to his [[Kapilavastu (ancient city)|hometown]], where Yaśodharā has Rāhula ask the Buddha for the throne of the [[Shakya|Śākya]] clan. The Buddha responds by having Rāhula [[pabbajja|ordain]] as the first Buddhist [[samanera|novice monk]]. He teaches the young novice about [[sacca|truth]], self-reflection, and [[anatta|not-self]], eventually leading to Rāhula's enlightenment. Although early accounts state that Rāhula dies before the Buddha does, later tradition has it that Rāhula is one of the disciples that outlives the Buddha, guarding the Buddha's dispensation until the rising of the [[Maitreya|next Buddha]]. Rāhula is known in Buddhist texts for his eagerness for learning, and was honored by novice monks and [[samaneri|nuns]] throughout Buddhist history. His accounts have led to a perspective in Buddhism of seeing children as hindrances to the spiritual life on the one hand, and as people with potential for enlightenment on the other hand.

== Accounts ==
Some early texts such as those of the [[Pali Canon|Pāli tradition]] do not mention Rāhula at all;{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=139}}{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=113}} but he is mentioned in later Pāli texts such as the [[Apadana|Apadāna]] and the [[atthakatha|commentaries]], as well as in the texts on [[Vinaya|monastic discipline]] of the [[Mūlasarvāstivāda]] and [[Mahasanghika|Mahāsaṇghika]] traditions.{{refn |For the [[Apadana|Apadāna]], see {{harvtxt |Crosby |2013 |page = 105}}. The other information is mentioned in {{harvtxt |Meeks |2016 |p=139}}.}} Earliest texts do not describe Rāhula in much detail, and he remains an ideal figure without much depth in character.{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |p=109}} Because of the lack of detail, especially after Rāhula's ordination, some scholars have argued Rāhula did not have an important role in Buddhism.{{sfn |Rahula |1978 |p=136}} Apart from the early texts, there are many [[post-canonical Buddhist texts]] that contain accounts about Rāhula.{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=139}} The accounts about Rāhula reveal that when Prince Siddhārtha leaves his palace to become a monk, his decision and subsequent spiritual quest is not just a personal matter, but also affects his family every step during the way, as they respond to and affect the prince on his path to [[enlightenment (Buddhism)|enlightenment]]. Thus, the prince's life before enlightenment is about two parallel spiritual lives, that of the Buddha and that of his family.{{sfn |Strong |1997 |pp=122{{en dash}}4}}

=== Birth ===
==== Pāli tradition ====
[[File:Siddhartha leaving sleeping Yashodhara and Rahula Roundel 17 buddha ivory tusk.jpg|thumb|Just before the prince leaves the palace for the spiritual life, he takes one look at his wife Yaśodharā and his just-born child.|alt=Ivory tusk showing a woman and a child sleeping on a bed, and a man standing besides the bed.]]
Rāhula is born on same day Prince [[Gautama Buddha|Siddhārtha Gautama]] renounces the throne by leaving the palace,{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}} when the prince is 29 years old,{{sfn |Keown |2004 |page=233}}{{sfn |Irons |2007 |p=400}}{{refn |group=note |According to some traditional sources, the prince is sixteen then.{{sfn |Keown |2004 |p=267}} Furthermore, some sources say that Rāhula is born seven days before Prince Siddhārtha leaves the palace.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/rahulamata.htm Rāhulamātā]}}{{sfn |Sarao |2017 |loc=Biography of the Buddha and Early Buddhism}}}} on the full moon day of the eight [[lunar month]] of the [[Hindu calendar|ancient Indian calendar]].{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=481}} That day, Prince Siddhārtha is preparing himself to leave the palace. The Pāli account claims that when he receives the news of his son's birth he replies "{{IAST|rāhulajāto bandhanaṃ jātaṃ}}", meaning 'A ''rāhu'' is born, a fetter has arisen',{{sfn |Powers |2013 |loc=Rāhula}}{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=481}} that is, an impediment to the search for enlightenment. Accordingly, [[Suddhodana|Śuddhodana]], Prince Siddhārtha's father and king of the [[Shakya|Śākya clan]], names the child ''Rāhula'',{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=481}} because he does not want his son to pursue a spiritual life as a mendicant.{{sfn |Irons |2007 |p=400}} In some versions, Prince Siddhārtha is the one naming his son this way, for being a hindrance on his spiritual path.{{sfn |Rahula |1978 |p=136}} Just before the prince leaves the palace for the spiritual life, he takes one look at his wife Yaśodharā and his just-born child. Fearing his resolve might waver, Prince Siddhārtha resists to hold his son and leaves the palace as he has planned.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}} Rāhula therefore becomes Prince Siddhārtha's first, but also last and only son.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Violatti |first1=Cristian |title=Siddhartha Gautama |url=https://www.ancient.eu/Siddhartha_Gautama/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140825002210/http://www.ancient.eu:80/Siddhartha_Gautama |archive-date=25 August 2014 |deadurl=no |website=Ancient History Encyclopedia |accessdate=29 October 2018 |date=9 December 2013}}</ref>{{sfn |Powers |2013 |loc=Rāhula}}

==== Other traditions ====
Other texts derive ''rāhu'' differently. For example, the Pāli ''[[Apadana|Apadāna]]'', as well as another account found in the texts of [[vinaya|monastic discipline]] of the Mūlasarvāstivāda tradition, derive ''rāhu'' from the eclipse of the moon, which traditionally was seen to be caused by the [[asura (Buddhism)|asura]] (demon) [[Rāhu]].{{sfn |Gnoli |1977 |page = 119}}{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}} The ''Apadāna'' states that just like the moon is obstructed from view by Rāhu, Prince Siddhārtha is obstructed by Rāhula's birth.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}}{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |p=105}} The Mūlasarvāstivāda tradition relates, however, that Rāhula is conceived on the evening of the [[great renunciation|renunciation]] of Prince Siddhārtha, and born six years later, on the day that his father achieves enlightenment,{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}} which was during a lunar eclipse.{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=119}}{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |p=105}} Further credence is given to the astrological theory of Rāhula's name by the observation that sons of [[list of Buddhas|previous Buddhas]] are given similar names, related to constellations.{{sfn |Rahula |1978 |p=136}}

Mūlasarvāstivāda and later Chinese texts such as the ''[[Dharmaguptaka#Abhiniṣkramaṇa Sūtra|Abhiniṣkramaṇa Sūtra]]'' give two types of explanation for the long gestation period.{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |pp=139{{en dash}}40}}{{sfn |Sasson |Law |2008 |p=69}} The first type involves the [[karma (Buddhism)|karma]] of Princess Yaśodharā and Rāhula himself.<!--139-40--> According to this interpretation, Yaśodharā has to bear the suffering of carrying a child in her womb for six years, because in a previous life as a cow herder she had refused to help her mother to carry a pail of milk and left it for her mother to carry the extra pail for six [[yojana|leagues]].{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |pp=139{{en dash}}40}}{{sfn |Sasson |Law |2008 |pp=69{{en dash}}70}} As for Rāhula, his karma was that in a previous life as a king he unintentionally had a sage wait for six days.{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=140}}{{sfn |Ohnuma |2012 |p=143}} In this life, he was a king and his brother, [[Bodhisattva#Early and Theravāda Buddhism|a previous life of the Buddha]],{{sfn |Rahula |1978 |p=136}} was a [[rishi|hermit]] who had taken a vow he would only live from what was given by people. One day, the brother broke his vow to take some water, and feeling guilty, asked the king to punish him.{{refn |group=note |In the texts of the Mūlasarvāstivāda tradition, the brother is another hermit, not the king, but he sends his brother to see the king for punishment.{{sfn |Péri |1918 |p=8}}}} The king refused to issue a punishment for such a trivial matter, but had his brother wait for his final decision and constrained in the royal gardens. After six days, the king suddenly realized he had forgotten about the hermit and immediately set him free, including apologies and gifts. As a result, Rāhula had to wait for six years before being born.{{sfn |Sasson |Law |2008 |p=69}}{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=117}} In some versions, the king did not allow a sage to enter his kingdom and accumulated the same bad karma of a long gestation period.{{sfn |Shirane |2013 |pp=168{{en dash}}9}} The later Mahāyāna commentary ''[[Mahāprajñāpāramitāupadeśa]]'' ({{zh|t=大智度論|p=Dazhidulun}}) does not blame Yaśodharā's karma for the six years gestation period, but does mention Rāhula's same karma as a king. However, in the 13th-century Japanese devotional text ''Raun Kōshiki'', Rāhula's late birth is seen as evidence of a miracle, rather than a result of karma.{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=141}}{{refn |group=note |In the Pāli texts, no long gestation period of Rāhula is mentioned, but a similar motif occurs in the story of Suppāvāsā, with a similar karma in a past life.{{sfn |Rahula |1978 |p=136}}}}

The second type of explanation consists of the more [[Religious naturalism|naturalistic]] argument that Yaśodharā is practicing [[Asceticism#Buddhism|religious austerities]] involving fasting and sleeping on a straw bed, which causes Rāhula's growth to slow down. She is involved in these practices during the time when Siddhārtha is practicing self-mortification. Later, King Śuddhodana prevents Yaśodharā from hearing any news of her former husband, and she gradually becomes healthier, as the pregnancy continues normally. However, some time later, the false rumor spreads that the former prince has died of his ascetism.<!--118--> Yaśodharā becomes very desperate and depressed, endangering her own pregnancy. When the news reaches the palace that Siddhārtha has attained enlightenment, Yaśodharā is overjoyed and gives birth to Rāhula. Buddhist Studies scholar [[John S. Strong]] notes that this account draws a parallel between the quest for enlightenment and Yaśodharā's path to being a mother, and eventually, they both are accomplished at the same time.<!--119-->{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=140}}{{sfn |Strong |1997 |pp=118{{en dash}}9}}
[[File:Rāhula seeing the Buddha.png|thumb|The Buddha returning home following his enlightenment, being greeted by Rāhula. The Buddha is represented by his footprints and throne. [[Amaravati|Amarāvatī]], 3rd century. [[National Museum, New Delhi]]. |alt=Stone relief with throne at the center and numerous figures surrounding the throne, including a mother and her child ]]
The late childbirth leads to doubts in the Śākya clan as to who is the father, as told in the Mūlasarvāstivāda tradition, in the ''Mahāprajñāpāramitāupadeśa'' and in the later Chinese ''Zabaozang jing'' ({{zh|t=雜寶藏經}}).{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=139}} Since Rāhula's birth was not regarded by Buddhists to be a virginal or miraculous birth, tradition had to explain that Prince Siddhārtha was actually the father.{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=119}} Yaśodharā responds by putting her child on a stone in a pond of water and making an [[sacca-kiriya|act of truth]] that if Rāhula is really her child, that he and the stone may not sink, but rather float back-and-forth. After she makes the declaration, the child floats according to her vow.{{sfn |Ohnuma |2012 |p=142}}{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=120}} Strong notes that this is a symbolic parallel with the attainment of enlightenment by the Buddha, described as the "further shore", and coming back to teach humankind.{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=140}}{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=120}} The ''Mahāprajñāpāramitāupadeśa'' contains another account, in which Prince Siddhārtha has several wives,<!--140--> and a wife other than Yaśodharā is the one defending her, being witness of her innocence.<!--141-->{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |pp=139{{en dash}}41}}

Furthermore, in both the Mūlasarvāstivāda texts and the ''Mahāprajñāpāramitāupadeśa'', there is a third account that proves Yaśodharā's innocence: the Buddha makes everyone around him look identical to him, through a [[ṛddhi|supernatural accomplishment]]. Rāhula proves that the Buddha is his true father when he manages to approach the real Buddha straight away.{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=120}}{{sfn |Edkins |2013 |pp=32{{en dash}}3}}{{refn |group=note |Yaśodharā had Rāhula present a gift to his real father, and he manages to find him straight away. In one version of the story the gift is a ring signet,{{sfn |Edkins |2013 |pp=32{{en dash}}3}} in another version it is an aphrodisiac.{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=120}}(''See [[Rāhula#Ordination|§ Ordination]], below.'')}} In a fourth story about proving Yaśodhara's purity, appearing in Chinese [[Avadana|Avadāna]]-style texts from the 5th century CE onward, she is burnt alive, but miraculously survives. In this account, King Śuddhodana orders that she be killed by burning her alive as punishment for her alleged impurity. Instead of being hurt by the flames, however, she performs an act of truth and the fire transforms into a pond of water. Śuddhodana welcomes her and her son back into the clan, and later becomes very fond of Rāhula.{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=142}} Some Chinese [[Jataka|Jātakas]] say that he recognizes his son Siddhārtha in the child, and manages to better cope with the loss of Prince Siddhārtha.{{sfn |Péri |1918 |p=22}} Religion scholar Reiko Ohnuma sees the fire ordeal as a metaphor that parallels the Buddha's enlightenment, a similar argument that Strong makes.{{sfn |Ohnuma |2012 |p=142}}

==== Historical analysis ====
Historian {{ill|Wolfgang Schumann|de|Wolfgang Schumann (Historiker)}} hypothesized that Prince Siddhārtha conceived Rāhula to please his parents, obtain their permission for leaving the palace and becoming a mendicant. He further speculated that the prince only conceived a son thirteen years after his marriage, because Yaśodharā initially did not want to bear a child, for fear that the prince would leave the palace and the throne as soon as the child was conceived.{{sfn |Schumann |2004 |p=46}} Orientalist and missionary {{ill |Noël Péri |fr}} believed that a late gestation period was more historically probable than the birth on the same day as in the Pāli tradition. She believed that if Prince Siddhārtha had left an heir to the throne, there would have been no sound reason for him to leave secretly at night. She further argued that there are many sources that try to explain the long gestation period, indicating an established tradition.{{sfn |Péri |1918 |pp=34{{en dash}}5}}

Besides historical speculations, Buddhist Studies scholar Kate Crosby argues that Prince Siddhārtha conceiving or giving birth to a son before his renunciation functions as a motif to prove that he is the best at each possible path in life: after having tried the life of a father to the fullest, he decides to leave it behind for a better alternative.<!--108--> In [[early Buddhism|early Buddhist]] India, being a father and bearing a son was seen as a spiritual and religious path as well as that of renouncing one's family, and Prince Siddhārtha's bringing a son in the world before renunciation proves he is capable of both.<!--108-9-->{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |pp=108{{en dash}}9}}

=== Ordination ===
[[File:Indian Museum Sculpture - Ordination of Rahula, Jamalgarhi (9220605766).jpg|thumb |Ordination of Rāhula, [[Indian Museum]], [[Kolkata]] |alt=Relief with child depicted at the center, and numerous figures at the sides, including the Buddha |upright=1.8]]
The accounts continue and describe that Rāhula is raised by his mother Yaśodharā and grandfather King Śuddhodana.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}} When Rāhula is seven,{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=481}} nine{{sfn |Meeks|2016 |p=136}}{{sfn |Schumann |2004 |p=123}} or fifteen{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |p=110}} years old, the Buddha returns to his home city of [[Kapilavastu (ancient city)|Kapilavastu]] at the request of Śuddhodana.{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=481}} The [[Mahavastu|Mahāvastu]] text from the [[Lokottaravāda]] tradition states that the royals try to prevent Rāhula from learning about the return of his father, but eventually he insists to know who the "Great Ascetic" about to arrive is, and he is told<!--133-4-->{{em dash}}indologist Bhikkhu Telwatte Rahula {{sic}} argues that the child was conscious of being without father.<!--134-->{{sfn |Rahula |1978 |pp=133{{en dash}}4}} Next, the Mahāvastu and the Mūlasarvāstivāda texts relate that Yaśodharā tries to tempt the Buddha back into his life as a prince by having Rāhula offer the Buddha an [[aphrodisiac]].{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=121}}{{sfn |Rahula |1978 |p=134}} Mūlasarvāstivāda texts continue and tell that her plan backfires when the Buddha has Rāhula eat it himself, and Rāhula therefore becomes enamored by his father and wishes to follow him.{{sfn |Ohnuma |2012 |p=145}}{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=121}} In the Pāli version of the story, on the seventh day of the Buddha's return, Yaśodharā takes Rāhula to see his father, the Buddha. She tells Rāhula that since his father has renounced the palace life and as he is the next royal prince in line, he should ask his father for his inheritance of crown and treasure, for his future sake when his grandfather will no longer rule the kingdom.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}}{{sfn |Rahula |1978 |p=134}} After the Buddha has had a meal, Rāhula follows the Buddha, asking him for his inheritance.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}} The Buddha does not try to prevent Rāhula from following him,{{sfn |Penner |2009 |p=68}} but in some versions of the story, some women from the court do try to, yet Rāhula persists.{{sfn |Péri |1918 |p=5}} He then looks at his father and says, "Pleasant is your shadow, [[shramana|recluse]]".{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=482}} Reaching the [[Nigrodharama|Park of Nigrodha]], where the Buddha is staying,{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=482}} the Buddha considers that the heritage of the throne will one day perish, and is tied up with suffering and stress: "I will give him the wealth I obtained under the [[Bodhi tree|tree of enlightenment]] thus making him the heir of an inheritance that does not perish."{{sfn |Penner |2009 |p=68}}
{{Quote box
| quote="The Prince Rāhula<br />
When he was nine years old<br />
Went forth from the home life<br />
To cultivate the Eightfold Path.<br />
Let us take refuge in and pay highest homage to Venerable Rāhula, who was born and went forth in order to benefit sentient beings."
| source = ''Raun Kōshiki''
| align = right
