| salign = right
| author = cited in {{harvtxt |Sekiguchi |1998 |p=16}}, translated by {{harvtxt |Meeks |2016 |p=144}}
}}
Most traditions relate that the Buddha then calls [[Sariputta|Śāriputra]] and asks him to ordain Rāhula. Rāhula ordains and is the first [[Samanera|''śrāmaṇera'']] (novice monk),{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}} and probably the first person in the [[sangha|monastic order]] to [[pabbajja|ordain in a formal way]].{{sfn |Rahula |1978 |p=83}} In some versions of the story, such as the 9th century Chinese ''Weicengyou Yinyuan Jing'' ({{zh|t=未曾有因緣經}}), a group of young boys ordain together with him.{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=143}}{{sfn |Edkins |2013 |pp=34{{en dash}}5}} The king discovers that now his grandson, [[Nanda (half-brother of Buddha)|his son Nanda]] and a number of other young men in the royal family have ordained and left the palace. Seeing his daughter grieve, he asks the Buddha that from now on, he only ordain people with the consent of his parents.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}}{{sfn |Keown |2004 |p=281}} Śuddhodana explains that Rāhula's ordination was a great shock to him. The Buddha assents to the proposal.{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=482}} This rule is later expanded in the case of women ordaining, as both parents and the husband have to give permission first to allow women to join the order of monks and nuns.{{sfn |Schumann |2004 |p=163}} In some versions of the story of Rāhula's ordination, Yaśodharā also protests, but relents in the end.{{sfn |Edkins |2013 |p=34}} The Mahāvastu states, however, that Rāhula asks to ordain himself, and is eventually granted permission by Yaśodharā and Śuddhodana.{{sfn |Rahula |1978 |p=134}}

Archaeologist Maurizio Taddei has noted that in many [[Gandhara]]n art depictions, Rāhula's life is linked to that of a previous life of the Buddha, the hermit [[Sumedho (Buddhist figure)|Sumedho]]. The Buddha giving his spiritual heritage to his son is compared to that of Sumedho allowing the [[Dipankara|Buddha Dīpaṃkara]] to walk over him, which is followed by Dipaṃkara predicting that Sumedho will become a [[Buddha (title)|Buddha]] in a future life.<!--119--> Both the figure of Gautama Buddha giving his inheritance to his son, and the figure of Dīpaṃkara Buddha giving his inheritance of [[Buddhahood]] to Sumedho are depicted with flames emitting from their bodies; both scenes are depictions of inheritance, [[filial piety|filial]] and disciple piety; both may have been considered by 5th-century Buddhists to be representations of "eager youth".<!--120-->{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |pp=119{{en dash}}20}}

=== Enlightenment and death ===
[[File:Ping Sien Si - 036 Rahula Thera (Thinking) (15638059169).jpg|thumb |Statue of Rāhula as monk at Ping Sien Si, [[Pasir Panjang]], [[Perak]], Malaysia |alt=Image of older monk with large eyebrows, sitting, with his hands hidden in his sleeves |upright=.8]]
According to the Pāli texts, once Rāhula has become novice, the Buddha teaches Rāhula regularly.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}} His instructions are very age-specific, using vivid metaphors<!--113--> and simple explanations.<!--115-->{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |pp=113, 115}} The Buddha's teachings have led to numerous [[sūtra|discourses]] being named after Rāhula in the [[Early Buddhist Texts]].{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}} Pāli texts relate how Rāhula grows up to become a novice that is diligent,<!--Nakagawa--> dutiful, amenable and eager for learning,<!--Malalasekera-->{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}}{{sfn |Nakagawa |2005 |p=34}} but there are also some early medieval Chinese and Japanese accounts which relate that Rāhula initially struggles with being a novice and only later appreciates the Buddha's teaching.{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=143}} Besides the Buddha, Śāriputra and [[Maudgalyayana|Maugalyayāna]] also help to teach Rāhula.<ref>{{cite web |author1=The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica |author2=Stefon, Matt |title=Shariputra {{en dash}} Disciple of the Buddha |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Shariputra |website=[[Encyclopedia Britannica]] |accessdate=30 October 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114220448/https://www.britannica.com/biography/Shariputra |archive-date=14 November 2018 |deadurl=no}}</ref>{{sfn |Nakagawa |2005 |p=34}} Rāhula often assists Śāriputra on his rounds for [[alms (Buddhism)|alms]] in the morning, and sometimes on other travels.{{refn |Both {{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}} and {{harvtxt |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}} mention the alms, but only {{harvtxt |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}} mentions the other travels.}} Every morning, Rāhula wakes up and throws a handful of sand in the air, making the wish that he may be counselled by good teachers as much as those grains of sand.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}}{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=482}}

Still in the same year as Rāhula's ordination, the Buddha teaches his son the importance of telling the truth in a discourse known as the ''Ambalatthika-Rāhulovāda Sutta''.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}}{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=481}} In this discourse, the Buddha teaches and encourages consistent self-reflection, to help let go of all evil actions that lead to harm to oneself and others, and to develop self-control and a moral life.{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=482}}{{sfn |Schlieter |2014 |p=319}} He encourages reflection before, during and after one's actions,{{sfn |Schlieter |2014 |p=319}} and explains that lying makes the spiritual life void and empty,{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=482}} leading to many other evils.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/am/ambalatthika_raahulovaada_s.htm Ambalatthika-Rāhulovāda Sutta]}}

When Rāhula becomes eighteen years old, the Buddha instructs Rāhula in a [[Kammaṭṭhāna|meditation technique]] to counter the desires that hinder him during his tours for alms. Rāhula has grown enamored with his own and his father's handsome appearance. To help Rāhula, the Buddha teaches another discourse to him. He tells Rāhula that all [[rūpa|matter]] is [[anatta|not-self]], and the same holds for the [[skandhas|different parts of one's mental experience]].{{refn |For the part on alms rounds, see {{harvtxt|Saddhasena |2003 |p=482}}. For the part about not-self, see {{harvtxt |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}} and {{harvtxt|Crosby |2013 |p=115}}.}} Having heard the discourse, Rāhula starts to practice meditation. His teacher Śāriputra recommends him to practice [[anapanasati|breathing meditation]],{{sfn |Shaw |2006 |pp=189{{en dash}}93}} but is unable to give Rāhula the instructions he needs.{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |p=110}} Rāhula therefore asks the Buddha to explain the meditation method in more detail and the Buddha responds by describing several meditation techniques to him.{{sfn |Shaw |2006 |pp=189{{en dash}}93}}{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |p=115}} On a similar note, the Buddha teaches Rāhula at a place called Andhavana about the [[anicca|impermanence]] of all things, and instructs him how to overcome the [[asava|"taints"]] inside the mind. As a result, Rāhula attains enlightenment.{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |pp=482{{en dash}}3}}{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |p=116}} Pāli tradition has it that the sermon is also attended by a [[crore]] of [[deva (Buddhism)|heavenly beings]], who once had vowed to witness the enlightenment of the son of the Buddha. Rāhula obtains the name "Rāhula the Lucky" ({{lang-pi|Rāhula-bhadda|italic=no |link=no}}; {{lang-sa|Rāhula-bhadra|link=no}}), which he himself explains is because of being the son of the Buddha, and because of having attained enlightenment.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}} and {{harvtxt |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}}. For the Sanskrit translation, see {{harvtxt |Burnouf |2010 |p=489}}.}}
[[File:Bodh Gaya - Buddha Statue - Rahula (9224949643).jpg|thumb |Statue of Rāhula, [[Bihar]], India. |alt=Statue of monk with one shoulder uncovered |upright=.7 |left]]
Later, the Buddha declares that Rāhula is [[etatagga|foremost]] among all disciples in eagerness in learning ({{lang-pi|sikkhākamānaṃ|italic=yes |link=no}}).{{sfn |Powers |2013 |loc=Rāhula}}{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}} and in the Pāli [[Udana|Udāna]], the Buddha includes him as one of eleven particularly praiseworthy disciples.{{sfn |Sarao |2004 |p=720}} Chinese sources add that he is also known for his [[khanti|patience]], and that he is foremost in 'practicing with discretion' ({{zh|p=mixing diyi}}), meaning practicing the Buddha's teaching consistently, dedication to the [[śila|precepts]] and study, but without seeking praise or being proud because of being the son of the Buddha.{{refn |For the aspect of dedication to the [[śila|precepts]] and to study, as well as avoiding being proud, see {{harvtxt |Irons |2007 |p=163}}; for the aspect of seeking praise, see {{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}}.}} Pāli texts give examples of Rāhula's strictness in monastic discipline. E.g. after there was a rule established that no novice could sleep in the same room as a [[bhikkhu|fully ordained monk]], Rāhula is said to have slept in an outdoor toilet.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}}{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=482}} When the Buddha becomes aware of this, he admonishes the monks for not taking proper care of the novices. After that, the Buddha adjusts the rule.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/t/tipallatthamiga_jat_16.htm Tipallatthamiga Jātaka (No.16)]}}

Pāli texts state that despite Rāhula being his son, the Buddha did not particularly favor him: he is said to have loved problematic disciples such as [[Aṅgulimāla]] and [[Devadatta]] as much as his own son, without any bias.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}}

Later in Rāhula's life his mother Yaśodharā becomes ordained as a [[bhikkhuni|nun]]. In one story, the nun Yaśodharā falls ill with [[flatulence]]. Rāhula helps her recover by asking his teacher Śāriputra to find sweetened mango juice for her, which is the medicine she is used to and requires. Therefore, with Rāhula's help, she eventually recovers.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/rahulamata.htm Rāhulamātā]}} and {{harvtxt |Crosby |2013 |p=112}}. Only Malalasekera mentions the mango juice and the recovery.}}

When he is 20 years old, Rāhula [[upasampada|fully ordains]] as a monk in [[Savatthi|Sāvatthī]].{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Baroni |2002 |p=261}} and {{harvtxt |Schumann |2004 |p=123}}. For the information that he was fully ordained in Sāvatthī, see {{harvtxt |Sarao |2013 |p=157}}.}}

Rāhula's death receives little attention in the earliest sources.{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |p=106}} Rāhula dies before the Buddha and his teacher Śariputra do. According to Pāli{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}} and Chinese{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}} sources, this happens as he is travelling through the [[Tavatimsa|second Buddhist heaven]] ({{lang-sa|Trāyastriṃśa|link=no}}). According to the early ''[[Ekottara Agama|Ekottara Āgama]]'' ([[Sarvastivada|Sārvastivāda]] or Mahāsaṅghika tradition) and the later ''Śāriputrapṛcchā'', however, Rāhula is one the four [[arhat|enlightened disciples]] whom Gautama Buddha asks to prolong their lives to stay in the world until the [[Maitreya|next Buddha Maitreya]] has risen, to protect the current Buddha's dispensation.{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=121}}

=== Previous lives ===
Following the Pāli and Sanskrit language sources, Rāhula is the son of the [[Bodhisattva#Early and Theravāda Buddhism|Buddha-to-be]] throughout many lifetimes.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}}{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}} He develops his habit of being amenable and easy to teach in previous lives.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}}{{sfn |Saddhasena |2003 |p=482}} Pāli texts explain that in a previous life he was impressed by the son of a previous Buddha, and vowed to be like him in a future life.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}}

== Legacy ==
[[File:Rahula - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|Rāhula on a Tibetan painting, 16th century |alt=Elderly monk in green and red robes, holding his hands in front of his chest.]]
Texts in the [[Mahayana|Mahayāna]] tradition describe that Rāhula is the eleventh of the [[16 arhats|16 Elders]] ({{lang-sa|Ṣoḍaśasthavira|italic=yes}}; Chinese tradition added two elders in the 10th century, making for 18 Elders{{sfn |Dong |2010 |p=33}}), enlightened disciples that have been entrusted with taking care of the Buddha's dispensation until the rising of Maitreya Buddha. Tradition states therefore that Rāhula is still alive, and resides with 1,100 of his pupils in an island called the 'land of chestnuts and grains' ({{zh|t=畢利颺瞿洲|p=Biliyangqu zhou}}).{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}} and {{harvtxt |Meeks |2016 |pp=137{{en dash}}8}}. For the number of 18, see {{harvtxt |Irons |2007 |p=400}}; {{harvtxt|Strong |1997 |pp=121{{en dash}}22}}. For the information that ''Biliyangqu zhou'' is an island, see {{harvtxt |Dong |2010 |p=59 n.11}}.}} The pilgrim [[Xuan Zang]] ({{circa}}602{{en dash}}664) heard a [[brahmin]] claim that he met Rāhula as an old man, who had delayed his passing into [[Nirvana (Buddhism)|Nirvana]] and was therefore still alive.{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=146}}{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=122}} On a similar note, Rāhula is considered one of the [[Ten Principal Disciples]],{{sfn |Keown |2004 |p=298}} known for his dedication to training new monks and novices.{{sfn |Baroni |2002 |p=262}} Moreover, he is considered to be one of the 23{{en dash}}28 masters in the lineage of the [[Tiantai]] tradition, one of the 28 in the [[Chan Buddhism|Chan]] lineage,{{refn |{{harvtxt |Welter |2004 |pp=462{{en dash}}3}} says [[Tiantai]] has only 23 patriarchs, whereas {{harvtxt |Irons |2007 |p=526}} states they later expanded to 28.}} and one of the [[eight arahants (Burma)|eight enlightened disciples]] in the Burmese tradition.{{sfn |Strong |1997 |p=122}}

As one of the enlightened disciples responsible for protecting the Buddha's dispensation, Rāhula has often been depicted in East Asian art. He is depicted with a large, "umbrella-shaped" head, prominent eyes and a hooked nose.{{sfn |Watters |1898 |p=340}}

The Chinese monks Xuan Zang and [[Faxian]] ({{circa}}320{{en dash}}420 CE) noted during their pilgrimages in India that a cult existed that worshiped Rāhula, especially in the [[Madhura]] area. Whereas monks would worship certain early male disciples following their particular specialization, and nuns would honor [[Ānanda]] in gratitude for helping to set up the nun's order, novices would worship Rāhula.{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |pp=135{{en dash}}6}} The two Chinese pilgrims noted that Emperor [[Ashoka|Aśoka]] built a [[stupa|monument]] in honor of Rāhula, especially meant for novices to pay their respects.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/r/raahula.htm Rāhula]}} Religious studies scholar Lori Meeks points out with regard to Japan, however, that Rāhula was not the individual object of any devotional cult, but was rather honored as part of a group of enlightened disciples, such as the 16 Elders.<!--132--> Exception to this was the 13th{{en dash}}14th century, when the figure of Rāhula became an important part of a revival of devotion to early Buddhist disciples among the old [[Nara prefecture|Nara]] schools,<!--131--> as [[kōshiki|chanted lectures]] (''kōshiki'') rites,<!--137--> and images<!--147--> were used in dedication to Rāhula. On regular [[uposatha|days of religious observance]],<!--137--> male<!--133--> and [[samaneri|female]]<!--134--> novices performed rites and gave lectures in honor of Rāhula. These were popular with the laypeople,<!--133--> as well as with priests that aimed to revive early Buddhist [[vinaya|monastic discipline]].<!--134-->{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |pp=131{{en dash}}3, 147}} In the ''kōshiki'' Rāhula was praised extensively, and was described as the "Eldest Child", ''eldest'' being a devotional term, since Prince Siddhārtha had no other children.{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=137, n.2}}

The ''[[Lotus Sutra|Lotus Sūtra]]'', as well as later East Asian texts such as the ''Raun Kōshiki'', relate that Gautama Buddha predicts Rāhula will become a [[Buddha (title)|Buddha]] in a future life,{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Rāhula}} named "Stepping on Seven Treasure Flowers" ({{lang-sa|Saptaratnapadmavikrama |link=no}}). In these texts, Rāhula was seen as a [[Bodhisattva#In_Mahāyāna_Buddhism|Mahāyāna type of Buddha-to-be]], who would save many [[sentient being (Buddhism)|sentient beings]] and live in a [[Pure Land]].{{sfn |Meeks |2016 |p=144}}

The exhortations the Buddha gives to Rāhula have also become part of his legacy. The ''Ambalatthika-Rāhulovāda Sutta'' became one of the seven Buddhist texts recommended for study in the [[Edicts of Ashoka|inscriptions]] of the Emperor Aśoka.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1960 |loc=[http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/am/ambalatthika_raahulovaada_s.htm Ambalatthika-Rāhulovāda Sutta]}}{{sfn |Hazzra |1995 |p=38}} This discourse has been raised by modern ethicists as evidence for [[consequentalism|consequentalist]] ethics in Buddhism, though this is disputed.{{sfn |Schlieter |2014 |p=319}}

Rāhula is mentioned as one of the founders of a system of Buddhist philosophy called the ''[[Vaibhāṣika]]'', which was part of the Sarvāstivāda schools.{{sfn |Burnouf |2010 |p=418}}{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |p=107}} He is also considered by some Thai schools of Buddhist [[Tantric Theravada|''boran'']] meditation to be the patron of their tradition, which is explained by referring to Rāhula's gradual development in meditation as opposed to the instant enlightenment of [[disciples of the Buddha|other disciples]].{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |p=121}}

=== Childhood in Buddhism ===
[[File:Novices_studying_Dhamma_and_Pali_language.jpg |The acceptance of Rāhula in the monastic order as a child set a precedent, which later developed into a widespread Buddhist tradition of educating children in monasteries.|thumb |alt=Teenage novices studying in class. |upright=1.2]]
From the narratives surrounding Rāhula several conclusions have been drawn with regard to Buddhist perspectives on childhood. Several scholars have raised Rāhula's example to indicate that children in Buddhism are seen as an obstacle to spiritual enlightenment,{{sfn |Thompson |Mauk |Kelly |Cook |2012 |p=61}} or that Buddhism, being a monastic religion, is not interested in children.{{sfn |Sasson |2014 |pp=594{{en dash}}5}} Education scholar Yoshiharu Nakagawa argues, however, that Rāhula's story points at two ideals of childhood which exist parallel in Buddhism: that of the common child, subject to the [[human condition]], and that of the child with a potential for enlightenment, who Crosby describes as a heroic disciple.{{sfn |Nakagawa |2005 |p=41}}{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |pp=119, 121}} Religion scholar Vanessa Sasson notes that although Prince Siddhārtha initially abandons his son, he comes back for him and offers a spiritual heritage to him as opposed to a material one. This heritage is given from a viewpoint of trust in the potential of the child Rāhula, presuming that the Buddhist path can also be accessed by children.{{sfn |Sasson |2014 |p=595}}

The acceptance of Rāhula in the monastic order as a child set a precedent, which later developed into a widespread Buddhist tradition of educating children in monasteries.{{sfn |Nakagawa |2005 |pp=34{{en dash}}5}} The numerous teachings given to Rāhula have left behind teaching material which could be used for teaching children of different ages,<!--117--> and were sophisticated for the time period.<!--118--> [[Theravada|Theravāda]] tradition further built on this genre, with Pāli manuals of religious teaching for novices.<!--117-->{{sfn |Crosby |2013 |pp=117{{en dash}}8}}

