'''Tracey Freeman''' (born 1948) is an Australian Paralympic athlete who won ten medals at two Paralympics.

==Personal==
Freeman became a quadriplegic due to [[polio]] at the age of two in 1951, while living in the Queensland city of [[Mount Isa]]. She went to the Crippled Children's Centre in the Sydney suburb of [[Redfern, New South Wales|Redfern]] until the age of 15, when she moved to the Mt Wilga Rehabilitation Centre. She developed a passion for sports competition, having been introduced to archery, field events and swimming during her rehabilitation. She then moved with her family back to Queensland and spent time at the Kingsholm Rehabilitation Centre in [[Brisbane]].<ref name="step">{{cite book|title=Step by Step We Conquer|publisher=Keeaira Press|isbn=0958529191|first=Vicki|last=Epstein|page=46}}</ref> She married shortly before the [[1972 Summer Paralympics|1972 Heidelberg Paralympics]].<ref name="step"/>

==Career==
Freeman's first national competition was the National Wheelchair Games in Sydney, where she won all the events she entered; she broke Australian records in discus, javelin, shot put and the 60&nbsp;m sprint, and won a gold medal in table tennis.<ref name="step"/> She was therefore selected for a place in the Australian team at the 1972 Heidelberg Paralympics, where she won three gold medals and broke world records in the Women's Discus 1B, Women's Javelin 1B, and Women's Shot Put 1B events, and two silver medals in the Women's 60&nbsp;m Wheelchair 1B and Women's Slalom 1B events.<ref name="step"/><ref name="IPC">{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/search.php?sport=all&games=all&medal=all&npc=all&name=Freeman&fname=T.&gender=all|title=Athlete Search Results|publisher=[[International Paralympic Committee]]|accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref> she was the most successful athlete at the games,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsa.org.au/life_site/text/sport/index.html|title=The history of people with disabilities in Australia – 100 years: Sport|publisher=Disability Services Australia|accessdate=28 February 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5v93Y0MPX?url=http://www.dsa.org.au/life_site/text/sport/index.html|archivedate=21 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the first Australian woman to win a gold medal at a Paralympic athletics competition,<ref name="wheelies">{{cite web|url=https://assets.clubsonline.com.au/assets/console/document/documents/110903-QLDUnderageAWDChamps-ResultsBook.pdf|title=2011 Queensland Underage AWD Athletics Championships: Results Booklet|publisher=[[Sporting Wheelies and Disabled Association]]|date=3 September 2011|accessdate=28 February 2012|format=PDF}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref> and one of Australia's first high-profile Paralympic competitors.<ref name="step"/>

She defended her national titles in athletics events at the 1973 National Wheelchair Games in [[Adelaide]] and won a gold medal in the wheelchair slalom.<ref name="step"/> She broke games records at the [[1974 Commonwealth Paraplegic Games]] in [[Dunedin]] and won gold medals in the discus and shot put and silver medals in the 60&nbsp;m and slalom at the first [[FESPIC Games]] in Japan the following year.<ref name="step"/> At the [[1976 Summer Paralympics|1976 Toronto Games]], she won three gold medals and three world records in the Women's 60&nbsp;m 1C, Women's Javelin 1C, and Women's Shot Put 1C events, and two silver medals in the Women's Discus 1C and Women's Slalom 1C events.<ref name="IPC"/> She hoped to participate in the [[1980 Summer Paralympics|1980 Arnhem Paralympics]] but a car accident just before the games forced her to withdraw from the competition.<ref name="step"/> She made a comeback in the early 1990s, when she once again won medals in national competitions and set Australian records, before retiring in 1996.<ref name="step"/>

==Recognition==
In 1976, Freeman became the first athlete with a disability to win ''[[The Courier-Mail]]'' Sportswoman of the Year award.<ref name="wheelies"/> In 2000, she received an [[Australian Sports Medal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=977709&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=Freeman, Tracey|publisher=It's an Honour|accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref> The [[Sporting Wheelies and Disabled Association]]'s Tracey Freeman Athlete of the Meet award is named after her.<ref name="wheelies"/> In December 2016, Freeman was inducted into the [[Australian Paralympic Committee awards#Australian Paralympic Hall of Fame|Australian Paralympic Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walsh|first1=Scott|title=Dylan Alcott wins double at Australian Paralympic Awards|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/olympics-2016/dylan-alcott-wins-double-at-australian-paralympic-awards/news-story/ee02e262ebc0ea1cfcf0e7ca58c06392|date=8 December 2016|work=The Courier-Mail|accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref>

